===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}

Early bronze inscriptions: {{liushu|p}} – acorn. Original form of {{och-l|皂}} through an intermediate variant [[皁]] (once also written as {{l|zh|草}}). Borrowed phonetically for "morning" sense.

Late bronze inscriptions: {{Han compound|日|棗|ls=psc|c1=s|c2=p|t1=sun}}, with {{zh-l|*棗}} sometimes simplified as {{zh-l|*朿}}.

Small seal script: {{Han compound|日|甲|ls=ic|t1=sun|t2=first}} – when the sun first rises. However, Xu Shen's interpretation is not based on oracle bones and bronzes inscriptions.

In some ancient texts, {{och-l|蚤}} was often used instead.

Unrelated to the ancient version of [[是]]: in this character, it doesn't represent an acorn but a spoon.

===Etymology===
Possible cognate found in {{cog|hmx-pro|*ntsi̯ouˣ||early}}, whence {{cog|mww|ntxov}} and {{cog|ium|nziou}} ({{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart, 2014}}; {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}), and {{cog|tai-pro|*ɟaːwꟲ||early morning}}, whence {{cog|th|เช้า}} and {{cog|khb|ᦋᧁᧉ}}. Note also similarities to {{cog|my|စော|t=early}}.

